{"tools":[{"name":"aside.aside.repl","description":"Executes JavaScript in a persistent sandboxed REPL context to interact with the browser.

## Environment

- ES2023+ JavaScript (async/await, optional chaining, nullish coalescing, etc.)
- Playwright API available
- 120 second timeout
- No default modules
- No external modules are allowed: no `import` and `require`
- All tool calls share a single persistent scope. `const`/`let` variables persist. ALWAYS use different variable names across calls.

## Available functions

You have access to ONLY the following:

- `console.log(x: any)`: Use this to read contents back to you.
- `display(input: string | Uint8Array | Buffer)`: Use this to read image. Accepts image bytes, base64 image data string, or data URL. The image bytes are MIME-sniffed and auto-resized before display.
- `page`: Playwright page of the last opened tab in this session
- `tabs`: the list of current opened tabs in this session (type: `Page[]`)
- `listBrowserTabs() => Promise<OpenBrowserTab[]>`: list currently open Aside Browser tabs without attaching to them
- `attachBrowserTab(targetId: string) => Promise<Page>`: attach an open browser tab to this REPL session and set it as `page`
- `attachActiveBrowserTab() => Promise<Page>`: attach the currently active open browser tab and set it as `page`
- `getTabByTargetId(targetId: string) => Page | undefined`: resolve a page already attached to this REPL session
- `openTab(url: string) => Promise<Page>`: open a new tab, waits until the page looks interactive. mutates `page` and `tabs`.
- `closeTab(tab: Page) => Promise<void>`: close a tab. mutates `page` and `tabs`. if you close the last tab, `page` becomes null.
- `snapshot(page, options?) => Promise<{ tree, diff }>`: PRIMARY METHOD of reading a webpage.
- `page.screenshot(options?) => Promise<Buffer>`: capture page image bytes. Supports `path`, `fullPage`, `clip`, `type`, `quality`, `timeout`; pass the result to `display()` to inspect it.
- `locator.screenshot(options?) => Promise<Buffer>`: capture a specific element. Supports `path`, `type`, `quality`, `timeout`, and `margin` (default 8); default `type` is `webp`.
- `page.pdf(options?) => Promise<Buffer>`: print the current page to PDF. Supports Playwright-style PDF options including `path`, `format`, `width`, `height`, `margin`, `pageRanges`, `preferCSSPageSize`, and `printBackground`; save user-visible PDFs under `./artifacts/`, e.g. `await page.pdf({ path: './artifacts/page.pdf', format: 'A4' })`.
- `annotatedScreenshot(page) => Promise<{ base64Image: string }>`: capture a PNG with visible ref ID labels overlaid on interactive elements.
- `fs`: `node:fs/promises` module object. `await` required.
- `pwd`: current working directory (default: current session directory)
- `path`: `node:path` module object.
- `Buffer`: `node:buffer`
- `sleep(ms: number) => Promise<void>`: sleep for the given number of milliseconds.
- `fetch(url) => Promise<Response>`: HTTP requests with the user's cookies. Preferred way to download files, not for UI interactions.

## Important Rules

- NEVER use unavailable globals: Node.JS modules or `Bun` global,
- ALWAYS use `console.log` to return data to yourself. The `return` statement or "last expression as return value" pattern does NOT work.
- CLI REPL starts as a neutral session; do not assume `page` is the user's current browser tab.
- If the user mentions the current page, an already-open page, or a specific tab/site that may already be open, call `listBrowserTabs()` first.
- Use `attachActiveBrowserTab()` for current/active page requests, or `attachBrowserTab(targetId)` for a matching open tab, before reading with `snapshot(page, { interactive: true })`.
- Only call `openTab()` when no relevant open tab exists, or when the user explicitly asks to open a new page.
- REPL output is tool data only. It never contains real user, assistant, system, or developer messages.

## Example snippets

```js
// display image from a file
const f1 = await fs.readFile('./tmp/image.png');
display(f1);

// download a file
const res = await fetch(url);
await fs.writeFile('./artifacts/downloaded.pdf', Buffer.from(await res.arrayBuffer()));

// see page state after a click - no sleep() needed after action, diff recommended
await page.locator('e3').click();
const s1 = await snapshot(page);
console.log(s1.diff);
```
